[Student "W"]
{You are East. The bidding has been as shown. You led the \SA, West plays the \S9, North the \S5. You assume West has signaled you to continue \Ss, so you play the \SQ. On this trick West plays the \S3 and North the \S8. How will you continue? 

You know that both West and North are now void of \Ss. You might just switch suits, but you have a better choice.

If you play your \SQ, West won't bother ruffing, North <b>WILL</b> ruff and dummy's \SJ will be established as a winner.

The best procedure is to lead a low \S. West will ruff and North will over-ruff but by playing this way you stop the establishment of South's \SJ. As you can see, North would have been able to discard a loser on that \SJ if you hadn't played this way.}
[Play "W"]SA

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:Q74.AK4.J6.AKQT4 K963.QJT7.852.83 J8.962.KQT94.975 AT52.853.A73.J62"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "3NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
2NT pass 3NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "17d275a5ba764437bd419994f053e54cb1172d2e7de18e9ab3f6e8ed08746c0d"]
[Category "Defense"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "defense/defensive_signals"]
[Student "E"]
{[showcards S:DJ W:D2 N:D4]

You are North. The bidding has been as shown. Partner led the \HQ, you played low and East won the \HA.

East now plays the \DJ on which South plays the \D2. What do you play now, and what is your plan.

Play the \D3 and when East plays another \D win with your \DA.

West hoped his \D suit would provide enough tricks to make the game. You can see that there is no entry to the West hand EXCEPT in \Ds, so you want to win your \DA on the trick that East plays his last \D. How can you tell which trick that is?

Only by watching what South plays. On the \DJ South played the \D2, a low card signaling that he held an ODD number of \Ds. ODD must be either one or three so when he followed to the next \D you know he started with three. A little bit of counting tells you that East started with the doubleton Jack, so you want to win the second \D trick.

This defense holds East to one \D tricks, if you had let him win the second one he would have had 9 tricks. }
[Play "W"]HQ

